11666111111166 1161111616 aaran dac„ ‘if that twas done with my consent, you have grounds for being angry with me.’ A gap is marked after this line, the lost verses being supposed to oontain Lysiteles’ explanation. But this single line implies sufficiently his innocense, which we need not suppose him to be at pains to prove. The spectators are aware of the facts, they know that with the best will in the world Lysiteles could not have restrained Lesbonicus, and it is in accordance with Plautus' custom to cut short such explanatione at the end of the play. See on v. 1097. Lysiteles feels quite easy about him- self, he is anxious to plead for his friend and does so at once. The marks of the persons are disordered iu the uss. But there cannot be any reason for making Callicles speak with Charmides. Their expla- nation is over and done with. The interlocutor here must be Lysiteles. Ussing and Goetz and Schoell make the speaker Callicles, but Niemeyer and Leonte, Ι think, certainly right in assigning the dialogue on from v. 1163 to Lysiteles.
